<script>
let slideIndex = 0;
showSlides();

function showSlides() {
  let i;
  let slides = document.getElementsByClassName("mySlides");
  let dots = document.getElementsByClassName("dot");
  for (i = 0; i < slides.length; i++) {
    slides[i].style.display = "none";  
  }
  slideIndex++;
  if (slideIndex > slides.length) {slideIndex = 1}    
  for (i = 0; i < dots.length; i++) {
    dots[i].className = dots[i].className.replace(" active", "");
  }
  slides[slideIndex-1].style.display = "block";  
  dots[slideIndex-1].className += " active";
  setTimeout(showSlides, 2000); // Change image every 2 seconds
}
</script>
 
<h2>No Limit Connect Design Goals</h2>
<br>
<h3>Privacy Matters</h3>
<p> - No registration or Third Party services.</p>
<p> - No Log Files.</p>
<p> - Whenever possible use direct connections from Person to Person.</p>
<br>
<h3>Network Scalability</h3>
<p> - A Network Host should be able to handle millions of User Hosts.</p>
<p> - There are 3 types of User Hosts.</p>
<p> -- Group Host</p>
<p> -- Chat Room Host</p>
<p> -- Random Connection Host</p>
<p> - Users should be able to setup a User Host on practically any device including old cell phones with just internet service.</p>
<p> - Users should be able to setup a User Host with little or no technical knowledge.</p>
<p> - Completely separate networks should be able to be hosted and run on a single cell phone or other low power device.</p>
<p> - Optionally the network key used as part of the encryption can be changed for completely private networks.</p>
